ce:section.ce:para:
Square wave voltammetry (SWV) is a highly sensitive technique with minimum charging current and high speed. SWV was employed for the analytical determination of nitroaromatics on the surface of VOCN7/GCE. The experiment was conducted with different concentrations of nitroaromatics (1.0 nM to 100.0 µM of 4-NP; 10.0 nM to 100.0 µM of DNP; 10.0 nM to 100.0 µM of DNT and 30.0 nM to 100.0 µM of TNP) and the results are shown in Fig. 8
                           . 4-NP showed a reduction peak at a potential of −0.6 V (Fig. 8(A)), whereas two reduction peaks were observed for DNP (Fig. 8(B)) and DNT (Fig. 8(C)) at the potential values of −0.35, −0.56 V and −0.35, −0.5 V, respectively and three reduction peaks were detected at −0.35, −0.7 and −0.85 V for TNP (Fig. 8(D)). Plots of SWV peak current versus analyte concentration (4-NP, DNP, DNT and TNP) are shown in the insets of Fig. 8(A-D). The limit of detection (LOD) of all the analytes were estimated using the equation LOD = 3.3(σ/S) [45,46], where σ is the standard deviation value of the response and S is calibration curve slope. The calibration equations used for the analytical purpose (i.e., calculation of LOD) of the studied nitroaromatics (4-NP, DNP, DNT and TNP) are given below:


4-NP, IP = 4.26 C4



                                    NP + 4.85 (r2 = 0.998, 1.0 nM to 0.9 µM);



DNP, IP = 3.45 CDNP + 3.04 (r2 = 0.996, 10.0 nM to 1.0 µM);



DNT, IP = 3.05 CDNT + 3.70 (r2 = 0.998, 10.0 nM to 1.0 µM);



TNP, IP = 4.28 CTNP + 10.60 (r2 = 0.997, 30.0 nM to 1.0 µM);
